<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="849" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d849">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 882.51/313B.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">American
                                Minister</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-27">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 27, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Falkner has received notice that the Liberian Government will probably
                            default on interest of the 1871 loan unless he secures aid. He has been
                            unable to do so. Bankers can not understand why, with the receipts as
                            reported, the Government has not provided for this payment. They are
                            skeptical as to whether correct reports of receipts have been made. They
                            want statement of receipts in the last six months, and also want to know
                            whether receipts reported for the last fiscal year were actual cash
                            receipts. Immediate action necessary, <pb facs="0788" n="672" xml:id="pg_672"/> as bankers have suspended further action pending
                            such report. Impress upon the Government that this matter is urgent and
                            vital to the continuation of the loan negotiations.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>